04949nam a22007095i 9780801470127DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014701277 a10.7591/97808014701272doi  a(DE-B1597)478508  a(OCoLC)979575815  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDL876.P3bB66 2005eb 7aTRU0020002bisacsh04a364.152/4/09485090481 aBondeson, Jan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlood on the Snow :bThe Killing of Olof Palme /cJan Bondeson. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (250 p.) :b2 maps, 20 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface: The Eighty-nine Steps -- t1. Death in Stockholm -- t2. Blood on the Snow -- t3. A Killer on the Loose -- t4. Hans Holmér Takes Charge -- t5. The First Main Suspect: The Oddball Schoolmaster -- t6. Red Herrings -- t7. The Kurdish Conspiracy -- t8. Ebbe Carlsson’s Secret Investigation -- t9. The Second Main Suspect: The Bayonet Killer -- t10. The Trials of Christer Pettersson -- t11. The Scapegoat Is Never Tarred -- t12. Conspiracy Theories -- t13. The Police Investigation Keels Over -- t14. Did Olof Palme Know His Killer? -- t15. Who Might Olof Palme Have Met? -- t16. The Crime of the Century -- tNotes -- tSources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Swedish Prime Minister Olof Palme, a major figure in world politics and an ardent opponent of apartheid, was shot dead on the streets of Stockholm in February 1986. At the time of his death, Palme was deeply involved in Middle East diplomacy and was working under UN auspices to end the Iran–Iraq war. Across Scandinavia, Palme's killing had an impact similar to that of the Kennedy assassinations in the United States—and it ignited nearly as many conspiracy theories. Interest in the Palme slaying was most recently stirred by reports of the death of Christer Pettersson, who was tried for the murder twice, convicted the first time, and then acquitted on appeal. In his investigative account of Palme's still-unsolved murder, the historian Jan Bondeson meticulously recreates the assassination and its aftermath. Like the best works of crime fiction, this book puts the victim and his death into social context. Bondeson's work, however, is noteworthy for its dispassionate treatment of police incompetence: the police did not answer a witness’s phone call reporting the murder just 45 seconds after it occurred, and further time was lost as the police sought to confirm that someone had actually been shot. When the police arrived on the scene, they did not even recognize the victim as the Prime Minister. This early confusion was emblematic of the errors that were to follow. Bondeson demolishes the various conspiracy theories that have been devised to make sense of the killing, before suggesting a convincing explanation of his own. A brilliant piece of investigative journalism, Blood on the Snow includes crime-scene photographs and reconstructions that have never before been published and offers a gripping narrative of a crime that shocked a continent.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAssassinationxInvestigationzSweden. 0aPrime ministerszSwedenxDeath. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 7aTRUE CRIME / Murder / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147012740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801470127423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801470127.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d201